previous_headings: Raw Data Format > Image capture and spatial biases
title: QuAnTeTrack
text: Digital recording methods (photography, photogrammetry, laser scanning) introduce inherent biases propagate entire analytical pipeline: Optical distortion (lens curvature, oblique angles) alters footprint geometry. Uneven resolution shadows may obscure anatomical features. Scale-bar misplacement (tilted coplanar surface) biases distance-based metrics, including step length, velocity proxies, sinuosity. Even small scaling errors systematically affect derived parameters.

title: QuAnTeTrack
text: test_direction() function provides powerful statistical framework comparing directions across different tracks within track R object. offers three distinct methods purpose, can selected using analysis argument: ANOVA, Kruskal-Wallis test, Generalized Linear Models (GLM), ensuring robust analysis even assumptions data distribution variance homogeneity violated. function requires track contains three footprints included analysis, statistical tests comparing mean directions require sufficient sample size generate meaningful results. threshold ensures comparisons statistically reliable robust. using "ANOVA" option, function first checks normality data Shapiro-Wilk test assesses homogeneity variances using Levene’s test. assumptions violated, user advised consider Kruskal-Wallis GLM methods instead. ANOVA method compares mean directions across tracks, significant differences detected, Tukey’s HSD test applied perform post-hoc pairwise comparisons. "Kruskal-Wallis" option, contrast, offers non-parametric approach compares median directions across tracks applies Dunn’s test pairwise comparisons significant differences found. method particularly suitable data meet assumptions required parametric tests. Alternatively, "GLM" option selected, function applies Generalized Linear Model (GLM) Gaussian family compare mean directions. emmeans package used compute pairwise comparisons, adjustments multiple comparisons following Tukey’s method, offering flexible approach dealing complex data distributions deviations normality. test_direction() function returns list detailed set results. provides normality results matrix containing Shapiro-Wilk test statistic p-value track, allowing user evaluate whether data follows normal distribution. function also outputs result Levene’s test, including p-value used assess whether variances across tracks homogeneous. ANOVA method selected, function delivers ANOVA table along Tukey HSD post-hoc results, enabling thorough examination differences groups. Kruskal-Wallis test, function returns overall test result alongside Dunn’s test post-hoc comparisons, providing non-parametric alternative analyzing differences central tendency. case GLM, output includes summary model fit along pairwise comparisons calculated via emmeans package, providing efficient method detect significant differences accommodating complex statistical models. flexibility comprehensiveness test_direction() function make versatile tool comparing directional data across multiple tracks. ability perform parametric, non-parametric, generalized linear model analyses ensures researchers can robustly test hypotheses related movement patterns, group behavior, ecological interactions, regardless underlying data structure.

title: QuAnTeTrack
text: track_intersection() function designed detect quantify unique intersections real movement trajectories, helping identify behavioral interactions coordinated movement, chasing, random exploration. comparing actual tracks simulated trajectories generated simulate_track() function, users can statistically assess whether observed intersections occur less frequently expected random conditions. input function track R object. statistical testing desired, test argument must set TRUE track simulation R object provided via sim argument. function offers several options modifying starting positions simulated tracks, controlled origin.permutation argument. set "None", simulated trajectories retain original starting points, making comparable actual data without spatial modification. "Min.Box" option randomly places starting points simulated tracks within minimum bounding box surrounding original starting points, simulating movement within defined area. "Conv.Hull" option provides precise alternative placing simulated tracks within convex hull encompassing original starting points, reflecting actual space occupied tracks. "Custom" option allows users specify area interest providing set coordinates (custom.coord) defining region’s vertices, particularly useful prior knowledge terrain features environmental factors suggests movement may spatially constrained. H1 argument specifies alternative hypothesis tested. set "Lower", function evaluates whether observed intersections significantly fewer generated simulations, may indicate coordinated gregarious movement. set "Higher", tests whether observed intersections significantly greater, indicative predatory chasing interactions. Users must provide value H1 test argument set TRUE. output track_intersection() function track intersection R object provides comprehensive assessment tracks intersect , applicable, intersections compare simulated datasets. core component object Intersection_metric, matrix details number unique intersection points pairs trajectories. test = TRUE, requires track simulation R object generated via simulate_track() provided sim argument, function produces additional outputs aimed statistically evaluating observed intersections. One Intersection_metric_p_values matrix, compares observed intersections derived simulations. p-value matrix indicates proportion simulated datasets intersection counts extreme extreme observed ones, depending selected H1 hypothesis (whether intersections expected fewer frequent random expectation). function also returns Intersection_metric_p_values_combined, single value summarizes overall statistical significance intersection metrics across trajectory pairs. combined p-value provides general indication whether total number intersections observed significantly different generated simulations, either supporting rejecting hypothesis investigation. Additionally, function provides Intersection_metric_simulations, list containing matrices intersection counts simulation iteration. detailed output allows users explore number intersections varies across multiple randomized scenarios, providing deeper insights robustness consistency observed patterns. comparing results simulated tracks, researchers can better evaluate whether observed intersections genuinely meaningful simply result random chance.

what: Clustering Tracks Based on Movement Parameters
title: QuAnTeTrack
text: Clustering tracks powerful approach detecting patterns movement may reveal specific behaviors strategies employed trackmakers. cluster_track() function designed process set tracks calculating various movement parameters classifying groups based similarities. Instead just comparing tracks pairwise, method allows identification broader behavioral patterns shared across multiple tracks. process begins preparing data, tracks containing fewer four steps filtered . Short tracks lack sufficient information movement patterns introduce noise clustering process. filtered, function calculates multiple movement parameters characterize trackmaker’s behavior. parameters include metrics turning angles, step lengths, sinuosity, straightness, velocity. cluster_track() function uses mclust package perform model-based clustering, particularly effective identifies natural clusters fitting various Gaussian mixture models data. Unlike methods impose arbitrary groupings, model-based clustering selects suitable model optimizing Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC). approach versatile, supporting single-parameter multi-parameter clustering, depending user’s analytical needs. one parameter selected, function uses simpler models equal variable variance. multiple parameters specified, examines entire range Gaussian models provided mclust. parameters used clustering specified via variables argument. Users can choose variety options, including "TurnAng" (mean turning angle), "sdTurnAng" (standard deviation turning angles), "Distance" (total distance covered), "Length" (total length trajectory), "StLength" (mean step length), "sdStLength" (standard deviation step length), "Sinuosity" (path tortuosity), "Straightness" (straight-line efficiency), "Velocity" (mean velocity), "sdVelocity" (standard deviation velocity), "MaxVelocity" (maximum velocity), "MinVelocity" (minimum velocity). flexibility allows users focus specific aspects movement combine multiple characteristics create comprehensive profile trackmaker behavior. data argument expects track R object veltrack argument requires track velocity R object. parameters used enhance clustering process incorporating speed-related information alongside spatial metrics. results clustering process important biological implications. grouping tracks similar movement parameters, researchers can infer behaviors produced tracks. instance, tracks characterized low sinuosity high velocity might indicate animals moving directly toward target, high sinuosity variable step lengths suggest foraging exploratory behavior. text: "error_partitioning" R object consisting list containing following elements: summary Data frame variance components per variable. Columns: variable, component, variance, percent, \(R^2_c\). Components track (biological), anatomical (within-track simulation variance), Residual (model simulation means). snr Data frame signal--noise ratio per variable. Columns: variable, bio_component (always "track"), bio_var, error_var, SNR. ratio $$SNR = Var(track) / [Var(anatomical) + Var(Residual)].$$ qc Compact quality-control table per variable SNR, qualitative SNR_rating ("weak", "moderate", "strong"), top_component percent, top_percent, \(R^2_c\), observer_note (always "anatomical-" function). models NULL. Placeholder kept consistency observer-inclusive workflow. observer models fitted . analysis_table Long data frame simulated values every track across Monte Carlo runs (variables joined track IDs simulation labels). formulae short note describing simulation-decomposition (within-track anatomical variance simulations, plus random-intercept model simulation means: \(y \sim 1 + (1|track)\); angles handled via sine–cosine). track_names Character vector internal track labels used analysis.

title: Partition anatomical-fidelity uncertainty (simulation-based) — anatomical_error_partitioning
text: function estimates much variability trackway metrics can attributed positional uncertainty track landmarks, rather true biological differences among trackways. asks, essence: "landmarks slightly misplaced error_radius, much affect computed parameters?" trackway, landmarks repeatedly perturbed within specified spatial tolerance, medial trajectory reconstructed, parameters recalculated across Monte Carlo simulations. resulting variance metric decomposed -track component (biological signal) within-track component (anatomical noise). error_radius represents expected imprecision reference-point digitization (e.g., preservation quality, erosion, deformation, subjective landmark interpretation). specifying realistic tolerance, users can evaluate sensitive metric anatomical taphonomic uncertainty identify parameters remain stable despite imperfect preservation. every track simulation, landmarks randomly displaced within circular area radius r, using either uniform model ("uniform") truncated Gaussian X Y SD = r/2 ("gaussian", truncated ±3 SD). perturbed landmark set converted medial trajectory (midpoints consecutive footprints, tps_to_track()), parameters recalculated via track_param(). metric \(Y\), total variance partitioned via law total variance : track (biological) — variance simulation means among tracks; anatomical — mean within-track variances across simulations; Residual — residual random-intercept model simulation means (observer terms simulation-setup). Angular variables (TurnAng, PaceAng) embedded sine–cosine space handle circularity avoid 0°/360° discontinuities (Fisher, 1995). signal--noise ratio quantifies robustness: $$\mathrm{SNR} = \frac{\mathrm{Var}(\mathrm{track})}                 {\mathrm{Var}(\mathrm{anatomical}) + \mathrm{Var}(\mathrm{Residual})}.$$ rule thumb: SNR < 1 — anatomical error exceeds biology (weak); SNR ~ 1–2 — biology anatomical error comparable (moderate); SNR > 2 — biology dominates (strong). compact QC table reports SNR, qualitative rating, top component percent, conditional \(R^2_c\).

code: # Example 1: PaluxyRiver, small jitter (2 cm), uniform noise # Expect relatively stable metrics and higher SNR. set.seed(1) ep_small <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = PaluxyRiver,   error_radius = 0.02,   variables    = c("Distance", "Straightness", "TurnAng"),   n_sim        = 10 ) #> Error in if ((Var_anatomical + Var_res) > 0) Var_bio/(Var_anatomical +     Var_res) else NA_real_: missing value where TRUE/FALSE needed ep_small$qc #> Error: object 'ep_small' not found  # Example 2: PaluxyRiver, larger jitter (8 cm) to see SNR drop # Inflate anatomical uncertainty; SNR should typically decrease. set.seed(1) ep_large <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = PaluxyRiver,   error_radius = 0.08,   variables    = c("Distance", "Straightness", "TurnAng"),   n_sim        = 10 ) #> Error in if ((Var_anatomical + Var_res) > 0) Var_bio/(Var_anatomical +     Var_res) else NA_real_: missing value where TRUE/FALSE needed ep_large$qc #> Error: object 'ep_large' not found  # Example 3: MountTom subset + Gaussian jitter (3 cm, truncated at ±3 SD) # Demonstrates alternative noise model and a reduced dataset. sbMountTom <- subset_track(   MountTom,   tracks = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 7, 8, 9, 13, 15, 16, 18) ) set.seed(2) ep_gauss <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = sbMountTom,   error_radius = 0.03,   variables    = c("StLength", "sdStLength", "PaceAng"),   n_sim        = 10,   distribution = "gaussian" ) ep_gauss$snr #>              variable bio_component     bio_var    error_var        SNR #> StLength     StLength         track 0.058217558 1.031312e-05 5644.99846 #> sdStLength sdStLength         track 0.001165249 2.973018e-05   39.19415 #> PaceAng       PaceAng         track 0.005343677 2.543369e-04   21.01023  # Example 4: PaluxyRiver with heterogeneous per-track tolerances # Alternate 2 cm / 5 cm across tracks; highlights mixed preservation quality. set.seed(3) rads <- rep(c(0.02, 0.05),             length.out = length(PaluxyRiver$Footprints)) ep_het <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = PaluxyRiver,   error_radius = rads,   variables    = c("TrackWidth", "Sinuosity", "PaceAng"),   n_sim        = 10 ) ep_het$summary #>                variable  component     variance    percent      R2_c #> TrackWidth.1 TrackWidth      track 3.740549e-02 99.7499311 0.9974993 #> TrackWidth.2 TrackWidth anatomical 9.377402e-05  0.2500689 0.9974993 #> TrackWidth.3 TrackWidth   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9974993 #> Sinuosity.1   Sinuosity      track 3.086845e-03 98.6831363 0.9868314 #> Sinuosity.2   Sinuosity anatomical 4.119198e-05  1.3168637 0.9868314 #> Sinuosity.3   Sinuosity   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9868314 #> PaceAng.1       PaceAng      track 8.498442e-02 99.7797710 0.9977977 #> PaceAng.2       PaceAng anatomical 1.875734e-04  0.2202290 0.9977977 #> PaceAng.3       PaceAng   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9977977  # Example 5: Angles only (circular handling via sine–cosine embedding) # Focus on orientation metrics; output includes averaged sin/cos components. set.seed(4) ep_ang <- anatomical_error_partitioning(   data         = PaluxyRiver,   error_radius = 0.04,   variables    = c("TurnAng", "PaceAng"),   n_sim        = 10 ) ep_ang$summary #>           variable  component     variance    percent      R2_c #> TurnAng.1  TurnAng      track 4.283363e-04 99.8192789 0.9981928 #> TurnAng.2  TurnAng anatomical 7.754955e-07  0.1807211 0.9981928 #> TurnAng.3  TurnAng   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9981928 #> PaceAng.1  PaceAng      track 8.475987e-02 99.7051248 0.9970512 #> PaceAng.2  PaceAng anatomical 2.506750e-04  0.2948752 0.9970512 #> PaceAng.3  PaceAng   Residual 0.000000e+00  0.0000000 0.9970512

title: Calculate combined probabilities of similarity or intersection metrics of tracks — combined_prob
text: combined_prob() function combines evidence multiple trajectory-based metrics, including distance-based similarity measures (e.g., DTW Fréchet) intersection metrics, using simulation-based hypothesis testing. distance-based similarity metrics (DTW Fréchet), smaller values indicate greater similarity trajectories. Accordingly, pairwise p-values computed using lower-tail Monte Carlo test (+1) correction (Phipson & Smyth, 2010): $$p = (1 + \#\{D_{sim} \le D_{obs}\}) / (nsim + 1)$$ tests whether observed trajectories least similar expected null model random movement. intersection metrics, direction test depends alternative hypothesis specified H1. H1 = "Lower", test evaluates whether observed number intersections significantly lower expected random simulations (e.g., coordinated gregarious movement). H1 = "Higher", test evaluates whether observed number intersections significantly higher expected (e.g., chasing predatory interactions). Combined pairwise p-values obtained jointly evaluating metrics across simulations, identifying simulation replicates metrics simultaneously extreme observed values, given respective directions. Monte Carlo test (+1) correction used, resulting pairwise p-values adjusted multiple comparisons using Benjamini–Hochberg (BH) procedure. addition, global combined p-value computed based single global statistic summarizing pairwise comparisons, providing overall assessment whether observed set trajectories departs random expectations across metrics considered.

title: Test for steady, acceleration, or deceleration along trajectories — mode_velocity
text: mode_velocity() function performs following operations: Spearman's Rank Correlation Test: non-parametric test assesses strength direction monotonic relationship two variables. require assumptions normality data linear relationship velocity step number. uses ranks rather raw values, making robust outliers suitable detecting general trends (acceleration deceleration) velocity data. Function Operation: trajectory trackvel list, function calculates Spearman correlation coefficient associated p-value velocity step number. Based p-value correlation coefficient, classifies trend "acceleration", "deceleration", "steady". trajectory contains fewer 3 steps, function returns message indicating insufficient data correlation analysis. Advantages: non-parametric nature allows flexibility data distributions reduced sensitivity outliers compared parametric tests. Effective detecting monotonic trends (either increasing decreasing) correlation statistically significant. Limitations: May unreliable small sample sizes (e.g., fewer 3 steps), providing potentially non-informative results. capture magnitude change provide detailed insights rate acceleration deceleration. Identifies monotonic trends based statistical significance distinguish different types monotonic relationships (e.g., steady acceleration vs. abrupt changes). Interpretation Results: Acceleration: p-value less 0.05 Spearman correlation coefficient positive. Deceleration: p-value less 0.05 Spearman correlation coefficient negative. Steady: p-value greater equal 0.05, indicating significant monotonic relationship. Usage Considerations: Ensure trajectory trackvel sufficient number steps meaningful analysis. detailed analysis velocity trends, consider complementary methods linear non-linear regression, specialized change point detection techniques.

text: function partitions variability selected metric components attributable biology (consistent differences among tracks) human sampling process: differences observers (inter-observer sampling error) differences repeated digitizations observer (intra-observer sampling error). Use audit reproducibility across people sessions, identify metrics remain stable despite digitizes , prioritize protocol changes (clearer landmark definitions, training, calibration) reduce measurement noise. Metrics whose variability dominated biological signal interpretable downstream (testing, clustering, classification), whereas dominated observer/replica effects warrant caution methodological refinement. metric model fits random intercepts track, observer, observer:track interaction. Replicate--replicate scatter within (observer, track) cell contributes residual (intra-observer sampling error). Random terms appear single level dropped automatically. $$y \sim 1 + (1|track) + (1|observer) + (1|observer:track).$$ Angular variables (TurnAng, PaceAng) handled sine–cosine space respect circularity avoid 0°/360° discontinuities: random-effects structure fit separately \(\sin(\theta)\) \(\cos(\theta)\), two variance decompositions averaged (Fisher, 1995). Robustness summarized signal--noise ratio $$SNR = \frac{Var(track)}{Var(observer) + Var(observer:track) + Var(Residual)}.$$ rule thumb: SNR < 1 — observer/replicate error exceeds biology; metric weak; SNR ~ 1–2 — biology error comparable; moderate robustness; SNR > 2 — biology dominates; strongly robust. compact QC table reports SNR, qualitative rating, top variance component percent, conditional \(R^2_c\); also flags whether inter-observer term estimable (>1 level). Practical designs: Full inter + intra: provide multiple observers multiple replicates per observer. observer observer:track estimable; replicate scatter residual. Intra-: set metadata$observer value rows provide replica >1 levels. track remains; replicate scatter residual. Inter-: set metadata$replica single level supply multiple observers. observer estimable; residual still represents replicate-level noise (present). Var(observer:track)=observer×track; Residual=intra-observer. tps <- system.file("extdata", "PaluxyRiverObsRep.tps",                    package = "QuAnTeTrack") RL <- rep(c("R","L"), length.out = 34) code: # Example 1: Simulate tracks using data from the Paluxy River # Default model (Unconstrained movement) simulated_tracks <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3) #> Warning: `model` is NULL. Defaulting to 'Unconstrained'.  # Plot simulated tracks with default settings and actual tracks plot_sim(PaluxyRiver, simulated_tracks)   # Example 2: Simulate tracks using the "Directed" model, representing movement toward a # resource simulated_tracks_directed <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Directed")  # Plot simulated tracks with specific colors and transparency for "Directed" model plot_sim(PaluxyRiver, simulated_tracks_directed,   colours_sim = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9"),   alpha_sim = 0.4, lwd_sim = 1, colours_act = c("black", "black"), alpha_act = 0.7,   lwd_act = 2 )   # Example 3: Simulate tracks using the "Constrained" model, representing movement along # a feature simulated_tracks_constrained <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Constrained")  # Plot simulated tracks with a different color scheme and width for "Constrained" model plot_sim(PaluxyRiver, simulated_tracks_constrained,   colours_sim = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9"),   alpha_sim = 0.6, lwd_sim = 0.1, alpha_act = 0.5, lwd_act = 2 )   # Example 4: Simulate tracks using the "Unconstrained" model (random exploratory # movement) simulated_tracks_unconstrained <- simulate_track(PaluxyRiver, nsim = 3, model = "Unconstrained")  # Plot simulated tracks with default colors and increased transparency for "Unconstrained" # model plot_sim(PaluxyRiver, simulated_tracks_unconstrained,   colours_sim = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9"),   alpha_sim = 0.2, lwd_sim = 1, colours_act = c("#E69F00", "#56B4E9"), alpha_act = 0.9,   lwd_act = 2 )   # Subsetting trajectories with four or more steps in the Mount Tom dataset sbMountTom <- subset_track(MountTom, tracks = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 7, 8, 9, 13, 15, 16, 18))  # Example 5: Simulate tracks using data from Mount Tom simulated_tracks_mt <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3) #> Warning: `model` is NULL. Defaulting to 'Unconstrained'.  # Plot simulated tracks with default settings and actual tracks from Mount Tom plot_sim(sbMountTom, simulated_tracks_mt)   # Example 6: Simulate tracks using the "Directed" model for Mount Tom simulated_tracks_mt_directed <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Directed")  # Plot simulated tracks with specific colors and transparency for "Directed" model for Mount # Tom plot_sim(sbMountTom, simulated_tracks_mt_directed, colours_sim = c(   "#E69F00", "#56B4E9",   "#009E73", "#F0E442", "#0072B2", "#D55E00", "#CC79A7", "#999999", "#F4A300",   "#6C6C6C", "#1F77B4" ), alpha_sim = 0.3, lwd_sim = 1.5, alpha_act = 0.8, lwd_act = 2)   # Example 7: Simulate tracks using the "Constrained" model for Mount Tom simulated_tracks_mt_constrained <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Constrained")  # Plot simulated tracks with different color scheme and increased line width for "Constrained" # model plot_sim(sbMountTom, simulated_tracks_mt_constrained, colours_sim = c(   "#E41A1C", "#377EB8",   "#4DAF4A", "#FF7F00", "#F781BF", "#A65628", "#FFFF33", "#8DD3C7", "#FB8072",   "#80BF91", "#F7F7F7" ), alpha_sim = 0.5, lwd_sim = 0.2, alpha_act = 0.6, lwd_act = 2)   # Example 8: Simulate tracks using the "Unconstrained" model for Mount Tom simulated_tracks_mt_unconstrained <- simulate_track(sbMountTom, nsim = 3, model = "Unconstrained")  # Plot simulated tracks with a different color scheme and transparency for "Unconstrained" model plot_sim(sbMountTom, simulated_tracks_mt_unconstrained, colours_sim = c(   "#6BAED6", "#FF7F00",   "#1F77B4", "#D62728", "#2CA02C", "#9467BD", "#8C564B", "#E377C2", "#7F7F7F",   "#BCBD22", "#17BECF" ), alpha_sim = 0.2, lwd_sim = 0.5, colours_act = c(   "#6BAED6",   "#FF7F00", "#1F77B4", "#D62728", "#2CA02C", "#9467BD", "#8C564B", "#E377C2",   "#7F7F7F", "#BCBD22", "#17BECF" ), alpha_act = 1, lwd_act = 2)

title: Plot trajectories and footprints — plot_track
text: plot_track() function designed diagnostic exploratory tool. primary purpose display raw spatial data (footprint coordinates interpolated trajectories) digitized, users can visually confirm data integrity conducting quantitative analyses. includes checking whether footprints correct order, whether trackways oriented consistently, whether interpolated trajectories align raw footprint data. Importantly, plots intended replace traditional ichnological illustrations. Hand-drawn maps outlines often convey information captured raw coordinate plots, tridactyl morphology, manus/pes distinction, taxonomic attribution, trackway orientation, frequently provide clearer communicative visual summaries ichnological material. contrast, plot_track() focuses plotting digitized data , without additional interpretation, stylization, symbolic annotation. goal offer reproducible, data-driven representation complements, rather supplants, traditional methods. Users encouraged treat plots quality-control visualizations help detect potential errors inconsistencies raw data prior downstream analyses, continuing rely classical ichnological illustrations detailed morphological taxonomic interpretation.

code: # Example 1: Plot Trajectories Colored by Velocity with Default Settings (MountTom dataset)  # Hip heights for each track in the MountTom dataset H_mounttom <- c(   1.380, 1.404, 1.320, 1.736, 1.364, 1.432, 1.508, 1.768, 1.600, 1.848,   1.532, 1.532, 0.760, 1.532, 1.688, 1.620, 0.636, 1.784, 1.676, 1.872,   1.648, 1.760, 1.612 )  # Calculate velocities using the default Method "A" V_mounttom <- velocity_track(MountTom, H = H_mounttom)  # Plot trajectories colored by velocity plot1 <- plot_velocity(MountTom, V_mounttom, param = "V") print(plot1)   # Example 2: Plot Trajectories Colored by Relative Stride Length with Default Settings # (PaluxyRiver dataset)  # Hip heights for each track in the PaluxyRiver dataset H_paluxyriver <- c(3.472, 2.200)  # Specify different methods for different tracks Method_paluxyriver <- c("A", "B")  # Calculate velocities using specified methods V_paluxyriver <- velocity_track(PaluxyRiver, H = H_paluxyriver, method = Method_paluxyriver)  # Plot trajectories colored by relative stride length plot2 <- plot_velocity(PaluxyRiver, V_paluxyriver, param = "RSL") print(plot2)   # Example 3: Plot Trajectories Colored by Velocity with Custom Line Width and Colors # (MountTom dataset)  # Custom colors and line width custom_colours <- c("blue", "green", "yellow", "red") custom_lwd <- 2  # Plot trajectories with custom colors and line width plot3 <- plot_velocity(MountTom, V_mounttom,   param = "V", lwd = custom_lwd,   colours = custom_colours ) print(plot3)   # Example 4: Plot Trajectories Colored by Relative Stride Length with Custom Line Width # and No Legend (PaluxyRiver dataset)  # Custom colors and line width custom_colours_rsl <- c("purple", "orange", "pink", "gray") custom_lwd_rsl <- 1.5  # Plot trajectories with custom colors, line width, and no legend plot4 <- plot_velocity(PaluxyRiver, V_paluxyriver,   param = "RSL", lwd = custom_lwd_rsl,   colours = custom_colours_rsl, legend = FALSE ) print(plot4)

what: Similarity metric using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) — simil_DTW_metric
title: Similarity metric using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) — simil_DTW_metric
text: simil_DTW_metric()  computes similarity metrics two trajectories using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW). allows different superposition methods align trajectories calculating DTW metric. function also supports testing simulations calculate p-values DTW distance metrics.

title: Similarity metric using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) — simil_DTW_metric
code: simil_DTW_metric(data, test = FALSE, sim = NULL, superposition = "None")

title: Similarity metric using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) — simil_DTW_metric
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. test Logical; TRUE, function compares observed DTW distances simulated trajectories calculates p-values. Default FALSE. sim track simulation R object consisting list simulated trajectories use comparison test = TRUE. superposition character string indicating method used align trajectories. Options "None", "Centroid", "Origin". Default "None".

title: Similarity metric using Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) — simil_DTW_metric
text: track similarity R object consisting list containing following elements: DTW_distance_metric numeric matrix pairwise Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) distances trajectories. entry represents DTW distance corresponding pair trajectories. DTW_distance_metric_p_values (test = TRUE) numeric matrix raw pairwise p-values, computed Monte Carlo tail tests (+1) correction (Phipson & Smyth, 2010): $$p = (1 + \#\{\text{extreme}\}) / (nsim + 1)$$. entry reflects probability observing DTW distance extreme observed one, given null hypothesis difference. DTW_distance_metric_p_values_BH (test = TRUE) numeric matrix Benjamini–Hochberg (BH) adjusted p-values controlling false discovery rate (FDR), applied across set unique pairwise tests (Benjamini & Hochberg, 1995). DTW_metric_p_values_combined (test = TRUE) single numeric value representing combined p-value across DTW distances (based global dominance criterion, evaluating many simulations observed distances smaller simulated ones across trajectory pairs simultaneously). indicates overall significance observed DTW distances relative simulations. DTW_distance_metric_simulations (test = TRUE) list containing matrices DTW distances simulation iteration, allowing inspection distribution DTW distances across randomized scenarios.

what: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: test_velocity() evaluates differences velocity means across different tracks using specified statistical test. includes options ANOVA, Kruskal-Wallis test, Generalized Linear Models (GLM), checks assumptions normality homogeneity variances. datasets two tracks, performs pairwise comparisons identify specific differences tracks.

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
code: test_velocity(data, trackvel, plot = FALSE, analysis = NULL)

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. trackvel track velocity R object consisting list element corresponds track contains velocity relative stride length data. plot logical value indicating whether plot boxplot velocities track (default FALSE). analysis character string specifying type analysis: "ANOVA", "Kruskal-Wallis", "GLM". Default "ANOVA".

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: list results statistical analysis diagnostic tests: normality_results: matrix test statistics p-values Shapiro-Wilk test track, rows test statistic p-value, columns track. homogeneity_test: result Levene's test, including p-value homogeneity variances. ANOVA (analysis "ANOVA"): list containing ANOVA table Tukey HSD post-hoc test results. Kruskal_Wallis (analysis "Kruskal-Wallis"): list containing Kruskal-Wallis test result Dunn's test post-hoc results. GLM (analysis "GLM"): summary GLM fit pairwise comparisons. plot (plot TRUE): boxplot velocities track generated displayed.

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: test_velocity function performs following operations: Condition Testing: Normality: Shapiro-Wilk test normality velocity data within track. Homogeneity Variances: Levene's test equal variances across tracks. Statistical Analysis: ANOVA: Compares mean velocities across tracks, assuming normality homogeneity variances. Includes Tukey's HSD post-hoc test pairwise comparisons. Kruskal-Wallis Test: Non-parametric alternative ANOVA comparing median velocities across tracks assumptions violated. Includes Dunn's test pairwise comparisons. GLM: Generalized Linear Model Gaussian family comparing means ANOVA assumptions met. Pairwise comparisons GLM conducted using estimated marginal means (least-squares means) emmeans package, computes differences group means adjusting multiple comparisons using Tukey’s method. Plotting: plot TRUE, boxplot velocities track generated.

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity
text: Humberto G. Ferrón humberto.ferron@uv.es Macroevolution Functional Morphology Research Group (www.macrofun.es) Cavanilles Institute Biodiversity Evolutionary Biology Calle Catedrático José Beltrán Martínez, nº 2 46980 Paterna - Valencia - Spain Phone: +34 (9635) 44477

title: Test for differences in velocity means with pairwise comparisons — test_velocity

what: Transform a *.tps file into a trackway R object — tps_to_track
title: Transform a *.tps file into a trackway R object — tps_to_track
text: tps_to_track() reads *.tps file containing footprint coordinates one several trackways transforms trackway R object.

title: Transform a *.tps file into a trackway R object — tps_to_track
code: tps_to_track(file, scale = NULL, R.L.side, missing = FALSE, NAs = NULL)

title: Transform a *.tps file into a trackway R object — tps_to_track
text: file *.tps file containing (x,y) coordinates footprints trackways. scale numeric value specifying scale meters per pixel. R.L.side character vector specifying laterality first footprint trackway. length vector must equal total number trackways sample. "L": first footprint corresponds left foot. "R": first footprint corresponds right foot. missing logical value indicating whether missing footprints trackway interpolated: TRUE, FALSE (default). NAs matrix two columns indicating missing footprints interpolated. first column gives number trackway containing missing footprints, second column gives number footprint missing within trackway. number rows equal total number missing footprints sample.

title: Transform a *.tps file into a trackway R object — tps_to_track
text: trackway R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list trajectories representing trackway midlines, interpolated connecting midpoints successive left–right footprint pairs (.e., footprints linked pace lines). Includes columns X, Y, IMAGE, ID, Side (set "Medial"). Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates associated metadata, Side column ("R" "L") missing marker ("Actual" "Inferred").

title: Transform a *.tps file into a trackway R object — tps_to_track
text: highly recommended *.tps file built using TPS software (Rohlf 2008, 2009). Trackways different number footprints (.e., landmarks) allowed. function transforms coordinates footprints trackway set trajectory coordinates. point trajectory calculated : $$Point_i(x,y)= (Footprint_i(x,y) + Footprint_{+1}(x,y)/2$$ number points resulting trajectory \(n_{footprints} - 1\). missing set TRUE, missing footprints can interpolated. interpolated footprint placed midpoint two adjacent footprints shifted laterally along direction perpendicular connecting segment. magnitude lateral shift estimated mean trackway width corresponding trackway, sign determined inferred anatomical side (left right) missing footprint. Inferred footprints flagged output.

title: Transform a *.tps file into a trackway R object — tps_to_track
text: Farlow, J. O., O’Brien, M., Kuban, G. J., Dattilo, B. F., Bates, K. T., Falkingham, P. L., & Piñuela, L. (2012). title: Calculate intersection metrics in tracks — track_intersection
code: track_intersection(   data,   test = NULL,   H1 = NULL,   sim = NULL,   origin.permutation = NULL,   custom.coord = NULL )

title: Calculate intersection metrics in tracks — track_intersection
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. test Logical; TRUE, function compares observed intersection metrics . Default FALSE. H1 character string specifying alternative hypothesis tested. Options "Lower" testing whether observed intersections significantly lower simulated ones (e.g., coordinated gregarious movement), "Higher" testing whether observed intersections significantly higher simulated ones (e.g., predatory chasing events). sim track simulation R object consisting list simulated trajectories use comparison test = TRUE. origin.permutation character string specifying method permutation coordinates simulated trajectories' origins. Options include "None", "Min.Box", "Conv.Hull", "Custom". Default "None". custom.coord matrix custom coordinates define vertices area permutation coordinates simulated trajectories' origins.

title: Calculate intersection metrics in tracks — track_intersection
text: track intersection R object consisting list containing following elements: Intersection_metric numeric matrix unique intersection counts trajectories. entry represents number unique intersection points corresponding pair trajectories. Intersection_metric_p_values (test = TRUE) numeric matrix raw pairwise p-values, computed Monte Carlo tail tests according H1, (+1) correction (Phipson & Smyth, 2010): $$p = (1 + \#\{\text{extreme}\}) / (nsim + 1)$$. entry reflects probability observing intersection count extreme observed one, given null hypothesis difference. Intersection_metric_p_values_BH (test = TRUE) numeric matrix Benjamini–Hochberg (BH) adjusted p-values controlling false discovery rate (FDR), applied across set unique pairwise tests (Benjamini & Hochberg, 1995). Intersection_metric_p_values_combined (test = TRUE) single numeric value representing combined p-value across intersections (based global statistic: sum pairwise intersections). indicates overall significance observed intersections relative simulations. Intersection_metric_simulations (test = TRUE) list containing matrices intersection counts simulation iteration, allowing inspection distribution intersections across randomized scenarios.

title: Calculate intersection metrics in tracks — track_intersection
text: track_intersection() function designed calculate number unique intersections trajectories evaluate statistical significance hypothesis testing based simulated tracks. Pairwise p-values computed Monte Carlo tail test according selected alternative hypothesis (H1), using (+1) correction avoid zero-values (see Phipson & Smyth, 2010): $$p = (1 + \#\{\text{extreme}\}) / (nsim + 1)$$ raw p-values adjusted multiple comparisons across set unique pairwise tests using Benjamini–Hochberg (BH) procedure false discovery rate (FDR) control (Benjamini & Hochberg, 1995). raw BH-adjusted p-value matrices returned output object, allowing users inspect either uncorrected corrected results. addition, global combined p-value provided, summarizing overall deviation null across pairs. framework provides robust means comparing observed intersections expected random conditions, intended testing specific behavioral hypotheses related trackmaker interactions. Hypothesis testing controlled H1 argument, defines alternative hypothesis: "Lower": tests whether observed intersections significantly fewer generated simulations. scenario corresponds hypotheses coordinated gregarious movement, parallel group movement result fewer intersections expected random. "Higher": tests whether observed intersections significantly greater generated simulations. scenario corresponds hypotheses predatory chasing interactions, one trackmaker follows crosses another, producing intersections expected random. choice H1 must match biological hypothesis investigation. explicitly specified test = TRUE, error raised. interpretation combined global p-value returned function directly influenced choice H1, determines whether test detects reduction increase intersection counts relative simulated dataset. addition hypothesis testing, track_intersection() function offers several options altering initial positions simulated tracks origin.permutation argument. available options include: "None": Simulated trajectories shifted compared based original starting positions. "Min.Box": Trajectories randomly placed within minimum bounding box surrounding original starting points. "Conv.Hull": Trajectories placed within convex hull encompasses original starting points, providing precise representation area occupied tracks. "Custom": Allows users define specific region interest providing matrix coordinates (custom.coord) specifies vertices desired area. option particularly useful certain spatial features environmental conditions known constrain movement. choice origin.permutation reflect nature behavioral hypothesis tested. example, using "None" appropriate testing intersections compare scenarios trackmakers originate specific locations. contrast, options like "Min.Box", "Conv.Hull", "Custom" suitable evaluating intersections differ tracks originated broader predefined area. track_intersection() function also allows integration similarity metrics computed using simil_DTW_metric() simil_Frechet_metric(). combination intersection counts similarity metrics can provide comprehensive analysis trackmakers interacted, whether movements coordinated independent, whether interactions consistent hypothesized behavioral patterns. Overall, selection H1 origin.permutation carefully considered light specific hypotheses tested. combining intersection metrics similarity measures, users can obtain deeper understanding behavioral dynamics underlying observed trackways.

title: Print track parameters — track_param
text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. gauge_size Numeric. Pes/manus length (width) used compute Gauge Trackway_width / gauge_size. NULL NA, Gauge returned NA.

title: Print track parameters — track_param
text: list lists, sublist contains computed parameters corresponding track. parameters included : Turning_angles vector turning angles track (degrees). Mean_turning_angle mean turning angles (degrees). Standard_deviation_turning_angle standard deviation turning angles (degrees). Path_length Total path length (meters), computed sum distances consecutive trajectory points. Beeline_length Straight-line distance (meters) first last points trajectory. Step_lengths vector step lengths track  (meters). Mean_step_length mean step lengths  (meters). Standard_deviation_step_length standard deviation step lengths  (meters). Stride_length vector stride lengths (meters), computed distances consecutive footprints side (L–L R–R), footprint order. Mean_stride_length Mean stride length (meters). Computed Mean_step_length * 2. Pace_length vector pace lengths (meters), computed distances consecutive contralateral footprints (L–R R–L) footprint order. Mean_pace_length Mean pace length (meters). Sinuosity sinuosity track (dimensionless). Straightness straightness track (dimensionless). Trackway_width Mean lateral separation left right footprints (meters), measured perpendicular inferred trackway axis. Gauge Trackway gauge (dimensionless), computed Trackway_width / gauge_size. Pace_angulation Mean interior angle (degrees) computed alternating triplets (L–R–L R–L–R). Step_angle Mean step angle (degrees), computed mean angle pace segment inferred stride/trackway axis.

title: Print track parameters — track_param
text: function calculates various movement parameters track provided data. uses following helper functions: trajr package: TrajAngles(): Calculates turning angles track. TrajDistance(): Calculates total distance covered track. TrajLength(): Calculates length track. TrajStepLengths(): Calculates step lengths track. TrajSinuosity2(): Calculates sinuosity track. TrajStraightness(): Calculates straightness track. circular package: circular(): Converts raw angles (radians) circular data type. mean.circular(): Computes circular mean turning angles. sd.circular(): Computes circular standard deviation turning angles. circular mean circular standard deviation returned degrees function. reference direction, 0 degrees, considered along positive x-axis. means angles measured counterclockwise positive x-axis, 0 degrees pointing directly along axis. detailed explanation appropriate methods analyzing circular data, refer Batschelet (1981). Circular mean turning angles computed : $$\overline{\theta} = atan2\left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{=1}^n \sin \theta_i, \frac{1}{n}\sum_{=1}^n \cos \theta_i\right)$$ : \(\theta_i\) \(^{th}\) turning angle radians. \(n\) total number turning angles. \(\sin \theta_i\), \(\cos \theta_i\) sine cosine components turning angle. \(\mathrm{atan2}(y,x)\) two-argument arctangent returns angle correct quadrant. Circular standard deviation turning angles computed : $$s_c = \sqrt{-2 \ln(\overline{R})}, \quad \overline{R} = \sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{=1}^n \cos \theta_i\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{=1}^n \sin \theta_i\right)^2}$$ : \(\overline{R}\) mean resultant length, measuring concentration angles around mean direction. \(n\) total number turning angles. \(\cos \theta_i\), \(\sin \theta_i\) trigonometric components angle. \(s_c\) circular standard deviation radians (converted degrees function). Sinuosity calculated according Benhamou (2004), defined equation 8. formula used refined version sinuosity index presented Bovet & Benhamou (1988), applicable broader range turning angle distributions require constant step length. sinuosity computed using formula: $$S = 2 \left[ p \left( \frac{1 + c}{1 - c} + b^2 \right) \right]^{-0.5}$$ : \(p\) mean step length (meters), \(c\) mean cosine turning angles (radians), \(b\) coefficient variation step length (meters). straightness index defined ratio D/L, : \(D\) beeline distance first last points trajectory (meters), \(L\) total path length traveled (meters). Straightness index based method described Batschelet (1981). According Benhamou (2004), straightness index serves reliable measure efficiency directed walk. However, suitable random trajectories, index random walk tends towards zero increasing steps. Thus, recommended use measure compare tortuosity random walks consist similar number steps.

text: data track R object, list consisting two elements: Trajectories: list interpolated trajectories, trajectory series midpoints consecutive footprints. Footprints: list data frames containing footprint coordinates, metadata (e.g., image reference, ID), marker indicating whether footprint actual inferred. H numeric vector representing height hip (meters) track maker. length vector match number tracks data. G Gravity acceleration (meters per second squared). title: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track
text: track velocity R object consisting list lists, sublist contains computed parameters corresponding track. parameters included : Step_velocities: vector velocities step track (meters per second). Mean_velocity: mean velocity across steps track (meters per second). Standard_deviation_velocity: standard deviation velocities across steps track (meters per second). Maximum_velocity: maximum velocity among steps track (meters per second). Minimum_velocity: minimum velocity among steps track (meters per second). Step_relative_stride: vector relative stride lengths step track (dimensionless). Mean_relative_stride: mean relative stride length across steps track (dimensionless). Standard_deviation_relative_stride: standard deviation relative stride lengths across steps track (dimensionless). Maximum_relative_stride: maximum relative stride length among steps track (dimensionless). Minimum_relative_stride: minimum relative stride length among steps track (dimensionless).

title: Calculate velocities and relative stride lengths for tracks — velocity_track
text: velocity_track() estimates speed stride length using classical formulas. shown Prescott et al. (2025), estimates may misleading— particularly tracks produced unconsolidated substrates, actual speeds can substantially lower calculated. Moreover, equal stride lengths may correspond different velocities, conversely, different stride lengths can sometimes reflect similar velocities, depending gait substrate conditions. values therefore treated caution, function subsequent functions incorporate velocity estimates. contrast, trackways formed firmer semi-consolidated surfaces, formulas reliable can provide useful estimates. Use best regarded comparative historical unless substrate context supports confident interpretation. #' velocity_track() function calculates velocities using two methods: Method : Based Alexander (1976), formula: $$v = 0.25 \cdot \sqrt{G} \cdot S^{1.67} \cdot H^{-1.17}$$ v: Velocity track-maker (meters per second). G: Acceleration due gravity (meters per second squared), typically \(9.81\ \text{m/s}^2\). S: Stride length, distance consecutive footprints (meters). H: Height hip track-maker (meters). coefficients \(0.25\), \(1.67\), \(-1.17\) derived empirical studies. coefficients adjust formula account different animal sizes gaits. method applies wide range terrestrial vertebrates used estimate velocity across different gaits. Method B: Based Ruiz & Torices (2013), formula: $$v = 0.226 \cdot \sqrt{G} \cdot S^{1.67} \cdot H^{-1.17}$$ v: Velocity track-maker (meters per second). G: Acceleration due gravity (meters per second squared), typically \(9.81\ \text{m/s}^2\). S: Stride length (meters). H: Height hip track-maker (meters). oefficient \(0.226\) method B refinement based updated data bipedal locomotion. Based Thulborn & Wade (1984), possible identify gaits track-makers basis relative stride length, follows: Walk: \(/H < 2.0\); locomotor performance equivalent walking mammals. Trot: \(2.0 \leq /H \leq 2.9\); locomotor performance equivalent trotting racking mammals. Run: \(/H > 2.9\); locomotor performance equivalent cantering, galloping, sprinting mammals.
